(c) Introduction section:

-We thought this dataset would be interesting to use because it could possibly be used to predict a persons body fat percentage using only a few simple and easy to perform measurements

  • This data has 19 variables and 252 observations. The response variable will be the amount of body fat in men. The other variables would be the explanatory variables. Our project can determine which explanatory variables are best. The data was supplied by Dr.A. Garth Fisher from The Human Performance Research Center at Brigham Young University. The body fat percentage was estimated using a type of underwater weighing technique.

Source Link: http://ww2.amstat.org/publications/jse/datasets/fat.txt

(d) Methods Section:

Background:

DESCRIPTIVE ABSTRACT: Percentage of body fat, age, weight, height, and ten body circumference measurements (e.g., abdomen) are recorded for 252 men. Body fat, a measure of health, is estimated through an underwater weighing technique. Fitting body fat to the other measurements using multiple regression provides a convenient way of estimating body fat for men using only a scale and a measuring tape.

SOURCE: The data were generously supplied by Dr.A. Garth Fisher, Human Performance Research Center, Brigham Young University, Provo, Utah 84602, who gave permission to freely distribute the data and use them for non-commercial purposes. Reference to the data is made in Penrose, et al. (1985).

VARIABLE DESCRIPTIONS: Columns

Case Number

Brozek - Percent body fat using Brozeks equation, 457/Density - 414.2

Siri - Percent body fat using Siris equation, 495/Density - 450

Density - Density (gm/cm^3)

Age - Age (yrs)

Weight - Weight (lbs)

Height - Height (inches)

Adip - Adiposity index = Weight/Height^2 (kg/m^2)

FFW - Fat Free Weight = (1 - fraction of body fat) * Weight, using Brozeks formula (lbs)

Neck - Neck circumference (cm)

Chest - Chest circumference (cm)

Abdomen - Abdomen circumference (cm) at the umbilicus and level with the iliac crest

Hip - Hip circumference (cm)

Thigh - Thigh circumference (cm)

Knee - Knee circumference (cm)

Ankle - Ankle circumference (cm)

Biceps - Extended biceps circumference (cm)

Forearm - Forearm circumference (cm)

Wrist - Wrist circumference (cm) distal to the styloid processes

url <- 'http://ww2.amstat.org/publications/jse/datasets/fat.dat.txt'
bodyfat <- read.table(url, sep = "",header = FALSE)
names(bodyfat) <- c("Case Number", "Brozek", "Siri", "Density", "Age", "Weight", "Height", "Adip", "FFW", "Neck", "Chest", "Abdomen", "Hip", "Thigh", "Knee", "Ankle", "Biceps", "Forearm", "Wrist")
#bodyfat

#Create categorical variables 

AgeCategory = bodyfat$Age
AgeCategory[bodyfat$Age >= 21 & bodyfat$Age <= 29] =  "Young Adult"
AgeCategory[bodyfat$Age >= 30 & bodyfat$Age <= 39] =  "Adult"
AgeCategory[bodyfat$Age >= 40 & bodyfat$Age <= 59] =  "Middle Age Adult"
AgeCategory[bodyfat$Age >= 60] =  "Senior"
bodyfat$Age.Category = AgeCategory

#Re-order columns

bodyfat <- bodyfat[ ,c(2, 6:8, 10:20)]

Due to the fact that we did not have a given categorical variable, we had to make our own as shown above. We decided to divide age into these different categories:

Young Adult - 21 through 29 years old

Adult - 30 through 39 years old

Middle Age Adult -40 through 59 years old

Senior 60 years old and above

Description of additional data preparation performed:

We had to put the data into labeled columns because they were labeled with the letter V, and it would be easier for us to know what we are retrieving from the data if we renamed the columns to the actual names of the respective variables. For all of our models, we used Brozek as our response variable. Therefore, we had to exclude some variables due to our choice in the response variables. We also excluded other variables due to said reason below. We want to exclude these variables- Siri , Case Number , Density, FFW, and Age We excluded Siri because it is another explanatory variable for the percentage of fat in men and we went with Brozek. We excluded Case Number because it is just a label for the number of participants in the dataset. Density was exluded because it is already used in Brozeks equation so it is already accounted for. Since FFW is found using Brozeks equation, we excluded it as well. Since we were not given a categorical variable, We had to make our own categorical variablewithin Age, so we excluded the Age category in order to use the new categorical variables we created.

Description of process we chose to follow:

Methods:

Model 1: Variable Selection

We started with creating a model that takes account of all the predictor variables.

#Full
bodyfat_model_full = lm(Brozek ~ ., data=bodyfat)

\(H_0:_{j_1}=_{j_2}=_{j_3}...=0\) where \(j\) is each predictor in bodyfat

\(H_1:\) At least one of \(_j0\) where \(j\) is each predictor in bodyfat

We choose to do a F-statistic test to find which variables were significant to the model with a significant level value = 0.1. Our p-value for the F-test was < 2.2e-16 which means there is a significant linear relationship between the response and at least one of its predictors. To cut down the model, we can remove any variable that has a single t-test p-value lower than 0.1.

#Remove variables that do not correlate well
which(summary(bodyfat_model_full)$coef[,4] > 0.1)

bodyfat_model_reduced = lm(Brozek ~ Neck + Abdomen + Thigh + Forearm + Wrist, data = bodyfat)

The variables that were removed are Age.Category, Weight, Height, Adip, Chest, Hip, Knee, Ankle, and Biceps. We removed all of age because only one of the three categories had a p-value lower than 0.1.

anova(bodyfat_model_reduced, bodyfat_model_full)

summary(bodyfat_model_full)$adj.r.squared
## [1] 0.7383632
summary(bodyfat_model_reduced)$adj.r.squared
## [1] 0.7119365

Based on ANOVA F-test, we get an extremely small p-value so we reject the null hypothesis and prefer the larger full model. Also our adjusted R-squared value for the reduced model decreased compared to the full model.

#residual plots
plot(bodyfat_model_full, which = 1)

plot(bodyfat_model_reduced, which = 1)

The Residuals VS Fitted values graph for the full model shows that the red line(a line that represents the datas average residuals at a certain fitted value) somewhat follows the expected value of zero line, except for some of the outliers that pull the red line away. Excluding those outliers, we would say that the full model does fulfill the constant variance assumption for linear regression. On the other hand, the Residuals VS Fitted graph for the reduced model has a red line that is more pulled away from the expected value of zero line. We are not entirely sure if fulfills the constant variance assumption. We are going to test both of these model with the Breuch Pagan test to ensure that the both of the models do fulfill the constant variance assumption.

library(lmtest)
bptest(bodyfat_model_full)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  bodyfat_model_full
## BP = 19.286, df = 16, p-value = 0.2541
bptest(bodyfat_model_reduced)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  bodyfat_model_reduced
## BP = 11.612, df = 5, p-value = 0.04051

The Breusch-Pagan test for the full model has a pvalue that is higher than a signicance leve of .1. Therefore, we do not reject the null hypothesis, and the full model does fulfill the constant variance assumption. The Breusch-Pagan test shows our reduced model rejects the null, and thus violates the Constance Variance assumption.

plot(bodyfat_model_full, which = 2)

plot(bodyfat_model_reduced, which = 2)

Looking at both qq plots graphs for the full model and the reduced model, we can see that most of the residuals of the data stays along the ideal residual line. Thus, we can assume that both graphs are normal, but we will still test them through the Shapiro-Wilk test to ensure that they are normal.

shapiro.test(resid(bodyfat_model_full))
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  resid(bodyfat_model_full)
## W = 0.99164, p-value = 0.1621
shapiro.test(resid(bodyfat_model_reduced))
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  resid(bodyfat_model_reduced)
## W = 0.99503, p-value = 0.5893

Both of the models have a pvalue that is higher than the significance level of .1; thus, the models do not violate the normality assumption for linear regression.

In conclusion, our original full model doesnt violate any assumptions. Based on the ANOVA F-Test, adjusted R-square value and the assumption tests, we would still prefer the original full model over the reduced model. We should look for another approach.

Because the ANOVA test generated a significantly low p-value, the original model (bodyfat_model_full) is the preferred model for predicting percentage of body fat in men.

Model 3: Stepwise Function

calc_loocv_rmse = function(model) {
  sqrt(mean((resid(model) / (1 - hatvalues(model))) ^ 2))
}

Forward, Backward, and Stepwise search:

We will first perform a Backward search for AIC and BIC

bodyfat_mod_back_aic = step(bodyfat_model_full, direction = "backward", trace = 0)
n = length(resid(bodyfat_model_full))
bodyfat_mod_back_bic = step(bodyfat_model_full, direction = "backward", k = log(n), trace = 0)

Now we perform a Forward search

bodyfat_mod_start = lm(Brozek ~ 1, data = bodyfat)
bodyfat_mod_forw_aic = step(
  bodyfat_mod_start, 
  scope = Brozek ~ ., 
  direction = "forward", trace = 0)

bodyfat_mod_forw_bic = step(
  bodyfat_mod_start, 
  scope = Brozek ~ . , 
  direction = "forward", k = log(n), trace = 0)

Finally, a Stepwise search

bodyfat_mod_both_aic = step(
  bodyfat_model_full, 
  direction = "both", trace = 0)

bodyfat_mod_both_bic = step(
  bodyfat_model_full, 
  direction = "both", k = log(n), trace = 0)

Lets compare their LOOVC RMSE values. We prefer to use Cross Validated RMSE to account for over-fitting so we can assess how well the model works in general, rather than just the observed data.

calc_loocv_rmse(bodyfat_model_full)
## [1] 4.466564
calc_loocv_rmse(bodyfat_mod_back_aic)
## [1] 4.042447
calc_loocv_rmse(bodyfat_mod_back_bic)
## [1] 4.086923
calc_loocv_rmse(bodyfat_mod_forw_aic)
## [1] 7.76628
calc_loocv_rmse(bodyfat_mod_forw_bic)
## [1] 7.76628
calc_loocv_rmse(bodyfat_mod_both_aic)
## [1] 4.042447
calc_loocv_rmse(bodyfat_mod_both_bic)
## [1] 4.086923

From here, we would choose AIC with Backward search if we use LOOVC RMSE as our metric. It performs better than any of the methods we tried earlier. However, we could do even better by exhaustively searching all possible AIC and BIC models.

Model 4: Exhaustive search

We can now use an exhaustive search approach in order to find the best model by checking every possible model. Since we have a reasonably sized dataset and not a large number of parameters, it is not difficult to check all possible models. Therefore, we will use the regsubsets() function in leaps R package.

#AIC model
#install.package("leaps")
library(leaps) 
bodyfat_mod_subs = summary(regsubsets(Brozek ~. , data = bodyfat))
n = length(resid(bodyfat_model_full))
p = length(coef(bodyfat_model_full))

Model 5: Accounting for Higher Order Terms

We now need to account for any higher order terms. We can use pairs() to check for any quadratic relationship with the response. We will also square all the relevant variables to create a large interaction model.

bodyFatCleaned = bodyfat
bodyFatCleaned$Age.Category = NULL
bodyFatCleaned$`Case Number` = NULL
bodyFatCleaned$Siri = NULL
bodyFatCleaned$Density = NULL
bodyFatCleaned$FFW = NULL
#Check for quadratic/ relationships
pairs(bodyFatCleaned, col = "dodgerblue")

There seems to be no qudratic relationship between the response and any of the relevant predictors. Now lets construct a full two-order interaction model with all the possible relevant variables. We will use both AIC and BIC.

bodyfat_bigFull_mod = lm(
  Brozek ~ (.) ^ 2, 
  data = bodyfat)

bodyfat_mod_back_intFull_aic = step(bodyfat_bigFull_mod, direction = "backward", trace = 0)
n = length(resid(bodyfat_bigFull_mod))
bodyfat_mod_back_intFull_bic = step(bodyfat_bigFull_mod, direction = "backward", 
                            k = log(n), trace = 0)

length(coef(bodyfat_bigFull_mod))
## [1] 134
length(coef(bodyfat_mod_back_intFull_aic))

Here we see that the new interaction model achieves lower LOOVC RMSE value than our previous non-interaction model from our exhaustive search. The BIC model gives us a LOOVC RMSE value of 3.96, with only 11 parameters. However, we could get better results. reduced_interaction_BIC = lm(Brozek ~ Weight + Adip  + Chest + Thigh + Wrist + Neck:Abdomen + Neck:Thigh + Chest:Abdomen, data = bodyfat)
length(coef(reduced_interaction_BIC))
## [1] 9
calc_loocv_rmse(reduced_interaction_BIC)
## [1] 3.894129

After cutting out Neck and Abdomen from the model, we notice an improved LOOVC RMSE and fewer paramters. However, we can further improve our results by creating a new interaction model using the variables we found from our best AIC model and squaring them.

bodyfat_big_mod = lm(
  Brozek ~ (Age.Category + Weight + Neck + Abdomen + Thigh + Forearm + Wrist) ^ 2, 
  data = bodyfat)

bodyfat_mod_back_int_aic = step(bodyfat_big_mod, direction = "backward", trace = 0)
n = length(resid(bodyfat_big_mod))
bodyfat_mod_back_int_bic = step(bodyfat_big_mod, direction = "backward", 
                            k = log(n), trace = 0)

length(coef(bodyfat_big_mod))
## [1] 43
length(coef(bodyfat_mod_back_int_aic))
## [1] 22
length(coef(bodyfat_mod_back_int_bic))
## [1] 9
calc_loocv_rmse(bodyfat_big_mod)
## [1] 4.199217
calc_loocv_rmse(bodyfat_mod_back_int_aic)
## [1] 3.841259
calc_loocv_rmse(bodyfat_mod_back_int_bic)
## [1] 3.91744

The new interaction model for AIC has better LOOVC RMSE of 3.841 than our full interaction model, but its bigger than our full interaction model with 22 parameters. We can reduce the model bit further by taking out Age.Category:Wrist parameter since they have rather high p-values.

bodyfat_final_mod = lm(Brozek ~ Age.Category + Age.Category:Thigh + Weight + Neck + Abdomen + Forearm  + Weight:Abdomen + Weight:Thigh + Weight:Wrist + Neck:Abdomen + Abdomen:Thigh + Forearm:Wrist, data =bodyfat)

## [1] 18
calc_loocv_rmse(bodyfat_final_mod)
## [1] 3.836224

After taking out Age.Category:Wrist, we have a smaller model with 18 parameters, and an even smaller LOOVC RMSE value of 3.836.

Checking for assumptions

plot(bodyfat_final_mod, which = 1:2)

bptest(bodyfat_final_mod)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  bodyfat_final_mod
## BP = 7.8445, df = 17, p-value = 0.9698
shapiro.test(resid(bodyfat_final_mod))
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  resid(bodyfat_final_mod)
## W = 0.99457, p-value = 0.5081

Breusch-Pagan Test does not reject, so constant variance assumption hasnt been violated. The Shapiro-Wilk test does not reject null either, so normality assumption hasnt been violated.

(e) Results: Final model:

bodyfat_final_mod = lm(Brozek ~ Age.Category + Age.Category:Thigh + Weight + Neck + Abdomen + Forearm  + Weight:Abdomen + Weight:Thigh + Weight:Wrist + Neck:Abdomen + Abdomen:Thigh + Forearm:Wrist, data =bodyfat)

Based on our analysis, we determined that model bodyfat_final_mod was the best model to use to predict the Percentage of Body Fat in men because it gave us the best LOOVC RMSE value, a reasonable number of parameters, and it didnt violate any normality or constant variance assumptions. We came to this model after trying numerous different methods. The most straightforward way of arriving at this model is by by finding the best AIC through exhaustive backwards search, then by using those variables in a two-order interaction model to find a new model that further improved the best of fit. We can then perform variable selection by t-test to further improve the model. Overall, our final model had shown a big improvement over our original full model in prediction and explanation.
